== Related events for Virtual Market ==

=== GameVket ===
A virtual exhibition event for indie games held in a virtual space. It's a new type of game event utilizing virtual space, where attendees can explore a vibrant venue showcasing diverse indie games while interacting with exhibitors in real time.
Both exhibiting and admission are free, and no specialized VR knowledge is required to participate. The inaugural event, titled “GameVketZero,” ran for seven days from April 29 to May 5, 2021.
=== ComicVket ===
Amidst the pandemic, as various events were canceled, ComicVket was born in March 2020 from a strong conviction that we must not let doujinshi creators lose their platform for expression. It is a virtual doujinshi convention event attracting over 100,000 attendees from around the world. ComicVket1 ran for four days from August 13 to 16, 2020. ComicVket2 ran for nine days from November 6 to 14, 2021.

=== MusicVket ===
Amid the COVID-19 pandemic, with numerous events canceled, this virtual music exhibition and sales event was born out of a strong conviction that indie music creators must not lose their platforms for presentation, and in response to user requests for “a music-themed virtual event.” “MusicVket1” ran for four days from August 13 to 16, 2020, featuring 127 participating circles and recording a total attendance of 80,000 visitors. ‘MusicVket2’ ran for five days from March 6 to 10, 2021, and “MusicVket3” ran for nine days from November 6 to 14, 2021.

=== VketMall ===
Born from the world's largest VR event, “Virtual Market,” this is a permanent, comprehensive shopping mall. Unlike the regular “Virtual Market,” there's no need to build your own booth from scratch. Instead, you choose an exhibition space from a selection of pre-made shops and can display a single item. Its defining feature is significantly lowering the barrier to entry, making it easy to showcase your work to the world.

=== VketReal ===
VketReal creates a “pararal” space—where virtual and real coexist and merge—in actual towns, enabling interaction and experiences while engaging with avatar culture and cutting-edge XR technology.

It features a visitor attraction model not centered on IP, celebrities, or advertising. Instead, individual creators, communities, companies, and even attendees themselves become “content,” building events where virtual and real spaces merge into places for play.

Starting from a base of core users, VketReal has grown immensely popular with families, travelers, couples, and even casual passersby, evolving into a new phenomenon where virtual culture naturally blends into the city.
